\begin_layout Standard
Considering solely the nonlinear advection terms, we get for the geopotential
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\frac{\partial\Phi}{\partial t} & =-\vec{V}\cdot\nabla\Phi=-\vec{V}\cdot\nabla\Phi'.
\end{align*}

\end_inset

For the VD, we get
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
\frac{\partial}{\partial t}\xi & = & -\nabla\cdot\left(\xi\vec{V}\right)\\
\frac{\partial}{\partial t}\delta & = & \vec{k}\cdot\nabla\times\left(\xi\vec{V}\right)-\nabla^{2}\left(\Phi'+\frac{\vec{V}\cdot\vec{V}}{2}\right)
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset

where all Coriolis-related terms vanished and we also compute the Laplacian
 on the perturbation 
\begin_inset Formula $\Phi'$
\end_inset

 rather than the full formulation.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Spherical harmonics
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We use state variables in physical space without a tilde, e.g.
 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

, and variables in spectral space denoted with a tilde such as 
\begin_inset Formula $\tilde{x}$
\end_inset

.
 Let the function converting data from spectral to physical space be given
 by
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
x=s2p(\tilde{x})
\]

\end_inset

and from physical to spectral space by
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\tilde{x}=p2s(x).
\]

\end_inset

The Laplace operator is then provided by
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\nabla^{2}(u)=lap(u).
\]

\end_inset

We also exploit the feature of the SHTNS library to compute the divergence
 and vorticity in spectral space for given velocities in physical space
 and denote this function by
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
(\tilde{\xi},\tilde{\delta})=vel2vd(u,v)
\]

\end_inset

and vice versa
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
(u,v)=vd2vel(\tilde{\xi},\tilde{\delta}).
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

